                   CSS Links
                     Exercise:1
Set the color of links to "red".


<style>
a
 {
  color: red;
}
</style>

<body>
  <h1>This is a heading</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph</p>
  <a href="http://w3schools.com">This is a link</a>
</body>
                   Exercise:2
Set the style when you mouse over a link (hover) to red.


<style>
a:hover
 {
  color: red;
}
</style>

<body>
  <h1>This is a heading</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph</p>
  <a href="http://w3schools.com">This is a link</a>
</body>
                 Exercise:3
Set the style for links to pages you have visited to red.


<style>
a:visited
 {
  color: red;
}
</style>

<body>
  <h1>This is a heading</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph</p>
  <a href="http://w3schools.com">This is a link</a>
</body>
                           Exercise:4
Remove the default underline style for links, but add a underline when you mouse over a link (hover).


<style>
/* unvisited link */
a:link
 {text-decoration: none;}

/* visited link */
a:visited
 {text-decoration: none;}

/* mouse over link */
a:hover
 {text-decoration: underline;}
</style>

<body>
  <h1>This is a heading</h1>
  <p>This is a paragraph</p>
  <a href="http://w3schools.com">This is a link</a>
</body>
                      Css Lists
                        Exercise:1
Set the list style for unordered lists to "square".


<style>
ul {
  
list-style-type
: 
square
;
}
</style>

<body>
<ul>
  <li>Coffee</li>
  <li>Tea</li>
  <li>Coca Cola</li>
</ul>
</body>
                      Exercise:2
Change the list's item marker to an image called 'bling.jpg':


<style>
ul {
  
list-style-image
: 
url("bling.jpg")
;
}
</style>

<body>
<ul>
  <li>Coffee</li>
  <li>Tea</li>
  <li>Coca Cola</li>
</ul>
</body>
                  Exercise:3
Remove the bullets/markers from the list items.


<style>
ul {
  
list-style-type
: 
none
;
}
</style>

<body>
<ul>
  <li>Coffee</li>
  <li>Tea</li>
  <li>Coca Cola</li>
</ul>
</body>
                       Exercise:4
Set the list style to I, II, III, instead of 1, 2, 3 for ordered lists.


<style>
ol {
  
list-style-type
: 
upper-roman
;
}
</style>

<body>
<ol>
  <li>Coffee</li>
  <li>Tea</li>
  <li>Coca Cola</li>
</ol>
</body>
